3bbma/application_vs_database_where_should"},{"short_id":"5bkb3b","created_at":"2025-09-18T09:59:24.000-05:00","title":"Elasticsearch: Search Index, Not System of Record","url":"https://www.paradedb.com/blog/elasticsearch-was-never-a-database","score":15,"flags":4,"comment_count":10,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"jamesgresql","user_is_author":true,"tags":["databases"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/5bkb3b","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/5bkb3b/elasticsearch_search_index_not_system"},{"short_id":"yn7jdd","created_at":"2025-09-18T09:46:02.000-05:00","title":"TernFS: an exabyte scale, multi-region distributed filesystem","url":"https://www.xtxmarkets.com/tech/2025-ternfs/","score":17,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"francesco","user_is_author":true,"tags":["c++","distributed","go"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/yn7jdd","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/yn7jdd/ternfs_exabyte_scale_multi_region"},{"short_id":"umwu0s","created_at":"2025-09-18T09:24:51.000-05:00","title":"Flipper Zero Geiger Counter Module","url":"https://kasiin.top/blog/2025-08-04-flipper_zero_geiger_counter_module/","score":6,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"rikhuijzer","user_is_author":false,"tags":["hardware"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/umwu0s","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/umwu0s/flipper_zero_geiger_counter_module"},{"short_id":"nhkmkg","created_at":"2025-09-18T09:11:31.000-05:00","title":"Website Inspo - Collected at the Component Level","url":"https://www.inspo.page/","score":4,"flags":0,"comment_count":2,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"HugoDaniel","user_is_author":false,"tags":["design","javascript"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/nhkmkg","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/nhkmkg/website_inspo_collected_at_component"},{"short_id":"cobbr5","created_at":"2025-09-18T08:54:46.000-05:00","title":"Announcing Rust 1.90.0","url":"https://blog.rust-lang.org/2025/09/18/Rust-1.90.0/","score":62,"flags":0,"comment_count":6,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"emschwartz","user_is_author":false,"tags":["release","rust"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/cobbr5","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/cobbr5/announcing_rust_1_90_0"},{"short_id":"rwgado","created_at":"2025-09-18T08:52:50.000-05:00","title":"How can we sandbox our development machines?","url":"","score":31,"flags":0,"comment_count":14,"description":"\u003cp\u003eI’d like to be able run code that’s potentially untrusted without risking other secrets on my machine.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePerhaps I’d like to try out a new package to see if it does what I want before I have to decide if I trust it or not\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePerhaps I’d like to run a tool on some sensitive data, and I’d like to sandbox it so that even if the code is malicious it cannot leak any secrets\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePerhaps I’d like to contribute to some project and run its build tools, but I don’t want to trust it with secrets on my machine\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eHow can I do those things easily?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eHere are some approaches that I’m aware of:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ethe dev container spec (but I don’t know what the security implications are)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003enix sandboxes its builds for reproducibility, I think\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eyou can do some things ad-hoc with docker or podman\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ee.g. \u003ccode\u003edocker run -u node -it -v .:/app node:24 yarn --cwd /app workspace server audit\u003c/code\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eyou can wrap some things with \u003ca href=\"https://justine.lol/pledge/\" rel=\"ugc\"\u003e\u003ccode\u003epledge\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI would like to be able to choose what permissions to grant to various programs, something like these:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eread/write/execute for filesystem paths\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003elistening/sending on localhost\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003elistening/sending on internet. Maybe granular by domain.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eenvironment variables\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003emaybe also communication with other processes, reading/writing other processes’ memory\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOther capabilities would be neat too (camera, keyboard, etc), but solutions that can only handle the first couple of things on the list above would still be useful to me.\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"I'd like to be able run code that's potentially untrusted without risking other secrets on my machine. \r\n\r\n- Perhaps I'd like to try out a new package to see if it does what I want before I have to decide if I trust it or not\r\n- Perhaps I'd like to run a tool on some sensitive data, and I'd like to sandbox it so that even if the code is malicious it cannot leak any secrets\r\n- Perhaps I'd like to contribute to some project and run its build tools, but I don't want to trust it with secrets on my machine\r\n\r\nHow can I do those things easily?\r\n\r\nHere are some approaches that I'm aware of:\r\n\r\n- the dev container spec (but I don't know what the security implications are)\r\n- nix sandboxes its builds for reproducibility, I think\r\n- you can do some things ad-hoc with docker or podman\r\n  - e.g. `docker run -u node -it -v .:/app node:24 yarn --cwd /app workspace server audit`\r\n- you can wrap some things with [`pledge`](https://justine.lol/pledge/)\r\n\r\nI would like to be able to choose what permissions to grant to various programs, something like these:\r\n\r\n- read/write/execute for filesystem paths\r\n- listening/sending on localhost\r\n- listening/sending on internet. Maybe granular by domain.\r\n- environment variables\r\n- maybe also communication with other processes, reading/writing other processes' memory\r\n\r\nOther capabilities would be neat too (camera, keyboard, etc), but solutions that can only handle the first couple of things on the list above would still be useful to me.","submitter_user":"cmcaine","user_is_author":true,"tags":["ask","security"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/rwgado","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/rwgado/how_can_we_sandbox_our_development"},{"short_id":"2zuusk","created_at":"2025-09-18T08:40:13.000-05:00","title":"Python 3.14.0rc3 is go","url":"https://pythoninsider.blogspot.com/2025/09/python-3140rc3-is-go.html","score":3,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"legoktm","user_is_author":false,"tags":["python"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/2zuusk","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/2zuusk/python_3_14_0rc3_is_go"},{"short_id":"tiv1ah","created_at":"2025-09-18T08:30:48.000-05:00","title":"Globally applying overlays onto Nixpkgs","url":"https://piegames.de/dumps/nixpkgs-global-overlays/","score":1,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"knl","user_is_author":false,"tags":["nix"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/tiv1ah","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/tiv1ah/globally_applying_overlays_onto_nixpkgs"}]